question_text:
To reduce the risk for health care - associated infections, health care personnel can use strategies including:
  1. 1. using methods besides a broom to pick up debris and, at a minimum, mopping the OR floor between procedures if it is visibly soiled.
  2. 2. mopping or wet vacuuming the entire floor during terminal OR cleaning.
  3. 3. concentrating cleaning on high-touch objects
  4. 4. waiting until after the surgical team has taken the patient from the room to start cleaning the OR.
  5. 5. moving the OR bed during room turnover to check for debris under the bed and when mopping to help ensure a clean floor.
  6. 6. performing a risk-benefit cost analysis if there is doubt about cleaning methods or a new process or product.
course_name: BACK TO BASICS: ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANING

question_text:
According to Leape et al, major steps that every leader should take to encourage a culture of respect include:
  1. 1. creating awareness of the problem and motivating others to take action.
  2. 2. establishing preconditions for a culture of respect.
  3. 3. setting expectation for acceptable behavior.
  4. 4. eliminating the causes of disrespectful behavior by listening to and engaging with staff members.
  5. 5. working to eliminate hierarchical structures, fostering professionalism, and demonstrating respect.
  6. 6. enforcing a zero tolerance policy for disrepectful behavior.
course_name: BACK TO BASICS: SPEAK UP

question_text:
The Data Entry Error report is sent to all Radiology supervisors daily (M-F). The report lists any suspected Exam Data Entry errors such as:
  • Exam start time after stop time
  • Exam start time equals stop time
  • Ex am start to exam stop greater than 12 hours (except NM multiday studies)
  • Exam start time is after transcription start time

A 55 y.o. female patient admitted with UTI presents with the following:
Admitting Vitals: HR 94, RR 20, T: 38, BP 104/65, P02: 98% RA
WBC -15.8
Creatinine 2.5

question_text:
A 55 y.o. female patient admitted with UTI presents with the following:
Admitting Vitals: HR 94, RR 20, T: 38, BP 104/65, P02: 98% RA
WBC -15.8
Creatinine 2.5
Based on these results the patient:
answer_text: b.	Is stable and no further needs are necessary
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text:
A 55 y.o. female patient admitted with UTI presents with the following:
Admitting Vitals: HR 94, RR 20, T: 38, BP 104/65, P02: 98% RA
WBC -15.8
Creatinine 2.5
Based on these results the patient:
answer_text: c.	Should receive IV abx for UTI and continue to monitor
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text:
A 55 y.o. female patient admitted with UTI presents with the following:
Admitting Vitals: HR 94, RR 20, T: 38, BP 104/65, P02: 98% RA
WBC -15.8
Creatinine 2.5
Based on these results the patient:
answer_text: d.	Meets severe sepsis criteria and the provider should be notified for further orders.
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A patient presented to the ED with pneumonia and AMS at 0900. In the ED a UA, urine culture, blood cultures x 2 were done and the patient was started on oral antibiotics. The patient is found to meet severe sepsis criteria an hour after admission at 1100.  Which of the following best describes the bundle elements the nurse should expect to implement to meet the sepsis bundle requirement?
answer_text: a.	Repeat the blood cultures x 2, administer broad spectrum IV antibiotic within 3 hours, and draw a lactate.
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A patient presented to the ED with pneumonia and AMS at 0900. In the ED a UA, urine culture, blood cultures x 2 were done and the patient was started on oral antibiotics. The patient is found to meet severe sepsis criteria an hour after admission at 1100.  Which of the following best describes the bundle elements the nurse should expect to implement to meet the sepsis bundle requirement?
answer_text: b.	Draw a lactate only since the patient has had blood cultures within the last 6 hours and is already on antibiotics.
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A patient presented to the ED with pneumonia and AMS at 0900. In the ED a UA, urine culture, blood cultures x 2 were done and the patient was started on oral antibiotics. The patient is found to meet severe sepsis criteria an hour after admission at 1100.  Which of the following best describes the bundle elements the nurse should expect to implement to meet the sepsis bundle requirement?
answer_text: c.	Notify the provider and expect orders for an IV broad spectrum antibiotic and a lactate to meet the remaining bundle requirement.
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A patient presented to the ED with pneumonia and AMS at 0900. In the ED a UA, urine culture, blood cultures x 2 were done and the patient was started on oral antibiotics. The patient is found to meet severe sepsis criteria an hour after admission at 1100.  Which of the following best describes the bundle elements the nurse should expect to implement to meet the sepsis bundle requirement?
answer_text: d.	Notify the provider and expect orders for repeat blood cultures, IV broad spectrum antibiotic, and a lactate. And the nurse should wait to administer the antibiotic until the blood cultures are done.
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A patient met severe sepsis criteria and the initial sepsis bundle was completed. Upon review of the lactate the RN sees the initial lactate result was 3. The RN should:
answer_text: a.	Continue to monitor the patient.
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A patient met severe sepsis criteria and the initial sepsis bundle was completed. Upon review of the lactate the RN sees the initial lactate result was 3. The RN should:
answer_text: b.	Obtain an order for a repeat lactate since the value is greater than 2.
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A patient met severe sepsis criteria and the initial sepsis bundle was completed. Upon review of the lactate the RN sees the initial lactate result was 3. The RN should:
answer_text: c.	Obtain an order for a 30ml/kg crystalloid fluid bolus.
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A 30ml/kg crystalloid fluid bolus should be ordered for which of the following?
answer_text: a.	Any 1 occurrence of SBP<90 , MAP <65, or SBP decrease >40
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A 30ml/kg crystalloid fluid bolus should be ordered for which of the following?
answer_text: b.	Any two occurrences of SBP <90,  MAP <65, or SBP decrease > 40  in a 3 hour period.
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A 30ml/kg crystalloid fluid bolus should be ordered for which of the following?
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A patient who met severe sepsis criteria and received a 30ml/kg fluid bolus. While completing the required 2 blood pressure reassessment within the hour after, the RN notices that the patient's SPB remains < 90. What is the best next step?
answer_text: a.	Notify the provider for additional fluid bolus.
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A patient who met severe sepsis criteria and received a 30ml/kg fluid bolus. While completing the required 2 blood pressure reassessment within the hour after, the RN notices that the patient's SPB remains < 90. What is the best next step?
answer_text: b.	Notify rapid response and the provider as the patient now meets septic shock criteria.
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

question_text: A patient who met severe sepsis criteria and received a 30ml/kg fluid bolus. While completing the required 2 blood pressure reassessment within the hour after, the RN notices that the patient's SPB remains < 90. What is the best next step?
answer_text: c.	Continue to monitor the blood pressures.
course_name: FY2021 SEPSIS RECOGNITION AND MANAGEMENT FOR MED-SURG NURSING

Ms Jones has been taking Xeloda for 3 months and her prescription says 4 tablets in the morning and 3 tablets in the evening. During your call she tells you that she has been taking 2 tablets every 12 hours because it doesn't make her feel well.

What do you do?
answer_text: A. Ask her about her side effects and tell her to continue the way she is taking them.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text:
Ms Jones has been taking Xeloda for 3 months and her prescription says 4 tablets in the morning and 3 tablets in the evening. During your call she tells you that she has been taking 2 tablets every 12 hours because it doesn't make her feel well.

What do you do?
answer_text: B. Tell her that she must stop immediately and make an appointment to see the MD.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text:
Ms Jones has been taking Xeloda for 3 months and her prescription says 4 tablets in the morning and 3 tablets in the evening. During your call she tells you that she has been taking 2 tablets every 12 hours because it doesn't make her feel well.

What do you do?
answer_text: C. Document your call in EMR and notify the Physician/RN directly.  Instruct the patient to contact the office to discuss dose change with the Physician.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text:
Ms Jones has been taking Xeloda for 3 months and her prescription says 4 tablets in the morning and 3 tablets in the evening. During your call she tells you that she has been taking 2 tablets every 12 hours because it doesn't make her feel well.

What do you do?
answer_text: D. Do nothing because some medication is better than her not taking it at all.

question_text: Ms Cruise has been on vacation and missed her first day of Gleevec therapy. She asks you if she can take 2 the following day like she used to do with her birth control. What would you recommend?
answer_text: A. Yes, you can double your dose any time you miss a dose as long as you don't take more than 2 days together.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text: Ms Cruise has been on vacation and missed her first day of Gleevec therapy. She asks you if she can take 2 the following day like she used to do with her birth control. What would you recommend?
answer_text: B. No, you should never double the dose of your medication. Skip the missed dose if it's too close to your next dose or take the missed dose as soon as you remember if it's not too close to your next dose.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text: Ms Cruise has been on vacation and missed her first day of Gleevec therapy. She asks you if she can take 2 the following day like she used to do with her birth control. What would you recommend?
answer_text: C. Yes, you can take as many doses as needed to get back on schedule.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text: Ms Cruise has been on vacation and missed her first day of Gleevec therapy. She asks you if she can take 2 the following day like she used to do with her birth control. What would you recommend?
answer_text: D. No, don't double the dose. Skip a day as a wash out and start your therapy again from day 1.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text:
Ms Jackson has just started taking Alecensa and has told you that it's too expensive so she picked up her refill but plans on taking it every other day to make it last longer.

What do you recommend?
answer_text: A. Counsel her on the side effects of therapy and let her know to call the office with any questions and document your call in EMR.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text:
Ms Jackson has just started taking Alecensa and has told you that it's too expensive so she picked up her refill but plans on taking it every other day to make it last longer.

What do you recommend?
answer_text: B. Remind the patient that the medication is most effective when it is taken as prescribed by the physician. Notify the physician and nursing staff she is having financial barriers to therapy and look into potential solutions or financial assistance and document your call in EMR.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text:
Ms Jackson has just started taking Alecensa and has told you that it's too expensive so she picked up her refill but plans on taking it every other day to make it last longer.

What do you recommend?
answer_text: C. Let her know that instead of taking her medication every other day, she can open the capsules and only take half so that it will last her the duration of therapy.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text:
Ms Jackson has just started taking Alecensa and has told you that it's too expensive so she picked up her refill but plans on taking it every other day to make it last longer.

What do you recommend?
answer_text: D. Document her change in therapy in the EMR but don't say anything to the physician or nursing staff.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text:
Mr Brown tells you that the physician has changed his therapy and he no longer needs his Cabometyx. He tells you that he met another patient in his support group that is taking the same medication and wants to give him the remaining pills.

What do you recommend?
answer_text: A. Advise him that medications should never be shared and he should call the local drug take back center, take it to a local medication drop off unit in the community, or contact the pharmacy for instructions on proper disposal.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text:
Mr Brown tells you that the physician has changed his therapy and he no longer needs his Cabometyx. He tells you that he met another patient in his support group that is taking the same medication and wants to give him the remaining pills.

What do you recommend?
answer_text: B. Tell him it's all right as long as you can call the other patient to verify the dose of his therapy.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text:
Mr Brown tells you that the physician has changed his therapy and he no longer needs his Cabometyx. He tells you that he met another patient in his support group that is taking the same medication and wants to give him the remaining pills.

What do you recommend?
answer_text: C. Instruct him to bring the medication back to the office and you will dispose of it for him.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text:
Mr Brown tells you that the physician has changed his therapy and he no longer needs his Cabometyx. He tells you that he met another patient in his support group that is taking the same medication and wants to give him the remaining pills.

What do you recommend?
answer_text: D. Tell him he can choose any of the above options, depending on what suits him the best.
course_name: 2021 RPH ORAL CHEMOTHERAPY ADHERENCE CALLS

question_text: If a patient has a laryngectomy, the patient can be intubated through the mouth if mechanical ventilation is needed.

question_text:
Which statements are true for laryngectomy patients:
1) The patient should have an ETT placed through the neck stoma during a respiratory emergency.
2) The upper airway maintains communication with the lower airway and the patient may be intubated through the mouth if necessary.
3) A speaking valve should NEVER be used for a laryngectomy patient.
4) Bagging can only be performed through the neck with a pediatric mask
course_name: LARYNGECTOMY

The SMI policy:
A. Instruct patient on use and purpose of incentive spirometer. Mark goal and 50% with yellow sticker /Place name on unit
B. Perform Smi: if patient reaches > 75% of their goal, turn over to nursing and inform them. Inform patient they are to do exercise q2 wa on own. Perform SMI daily as long as the patient is in the 50-75% range
C. If patient is less than 50% of predicted value, initiate IPPB with SMI BID or with scheduled treatment until they can achieve greater than 50% of their goal for 2 consecutive visits
D. Document Education/Document Goal/Document number of attempts

question_text:
Which of the following are components of the Thoracic Surgery protocol?
A. Institute SMI and IPPB on all patients with a unit dose of Albuterol (2.5mg) and Ipratroprium Bromide (0.5mg) at a frequency of every 8 hours for 24 hours.
B. IPPB PIP of 15cmH20.
C. Patient assessment including pre and post vital signs (heart and respiratory rate, breath sounds, sputum production, Sp02 and level of consciousness)
D. After 24 hours, if the bronchodilator is not indicated, it may be changed to PRN.
course_name: 2021 RESPIRATORY ADULT ICU COMPETENCY

question_text:
Your patient remains intubated in APV-CMV mode after surgery: Vt 500mL, RR 14,
PEEP 5. Fi02 50%. Exh Vt 515mL, Total RR 16, Sp02 99%. No pressors, no sedation.
All pain medications are PRN. Patient is awake and follows commands.
AM ABG results: 7.47 / 30 / 105 / 25 / 1.8. EtC02 31.
What is the next appropriate course of action?
A. Report the ABG to the physician and make changes only if ordered.
B. Decrease the set rate to 12bpm.
C. Decrease Fi02
D. Decrease the Vt to 450mL.
E. Start the SBT using either ASV 100%MV or CPAP/PS, notify the physician and RN and document in the EMR .
course_name: 2021 RESPIRATORY ADULT ICU COMPETENCY

question_text: 49 F, 5'5", with a history of chronic renal failure, CHF, pulmonary edema, morbid obesity, and HTN is admitted to the ICU after having missed her dialysis treatment.  She arrives on the unit wearing a NRB mask at 15lpm, Sp02 92%.  She presents with crackles throughout, labored breathing in a tripod position.  CXR shows pulmonary edema.  ABG results on current settings: 7.29/54/69/29/3.1.  HR 100.  B/P 115/69.  The decision is made to intubate and sedate.  Per protocol, what initial mode and settings would be most appropriate?
answer_text: A. APV-CMV Vt 500, RR 18, PEEP 12, Fi02 75%
course_name: 2021 RESPIRATORY ADULT ICU COMPETENCY

question_text:
It is day 3 after trach tube placement in the OR. There is no skin barrier in place, sutures remain intact, and you notice skin breakdown below the flange.
Which statements regarding skin breakdown are TRUE?
A. Trach sutures may be removed prior to 5 days when new skin breakdown occurs. Notify the physician once sutures are removed, place a skin barrier and write a Progress note.
B. An incident report must be logged, a physician promptly notified and Progress Note written.
C. Notify the RN to consult wound care and document the skin breakdown in Cerner.
D. If ointment is at bedside, RT may scan the medication before applying it when scheduled trach care is done.
course_name: 2021 RESPIRATORY ADULT ICU COMPETENCY

Laryngectomy patients
What is the appropriate way to ventilate with a bag/mask for a laryngectomy patient without an artificial airway?
answer_text: 1. Cover the laryngectomy stoma with your hand or gauze and bag through the mouth with the AMBU bag.
course_name: 2021 RESPIRATORY ADULT ICU COMPETENCY

question_text:
Laryngectomy patients
What is the appropriate way to ventilate with a bag/mask for a laryngectomy patient without an artificial airway?
answer_text: 2. Use an adult AMBU bag and a pediatric mask over the laryngectomy stoma to provide ventilation.
course_name: 2021 RESPIRATORY ADULT ICU COMPETENCY

question_text:
Laryngectomy patients

question_text:
Which of the following are components of the Thoracic Surgery protocol?
A. Institute SMI and IPPB on all patients with a unit dose of Albuterol (2.5mg) and Ipratroprium Bromide (0.5mg) at a frequency of every 8 hours for 24 hours. B. IPPB PIP of 15cmH20. C. Patient assessment including pre and post vital signs (heart and respiratory rate, breath sounds, sputum production, Sp02 and level of consciousness) D. After 24 hours, if the bronchodilator is not indicated, it may be changed to PRN.

Your patient remains intubated in APV-CMV mode after surgery: Vt 500mL, RR 14, PEEP 5. Fi02 50%. Exh Vt 515mL, Total RR 16, Sp02 99%. No pressors, no sedation. All pain medications are PRN. ICU shift summaries H. RT evaluation and treat consults
course_name: 2021 RESPIRATORY ICU COMPETENCY

question_text:
Laryngectomy patients
What is the appropriate way to ventilate with a bag/mask for a laryngectomy patient without an artificial airway?
answer_text: 1. Cover the laryngectomy stoma with your hand or gauze and bag through the mouth with the AMBU bag.
course_name: 2021 RESPIRATORY ICU COMPETENCY

question_text:
Laryngectomy patients
What is the appropriate way to ventilate with a bag/mask for a laryngectomy patient without an artificial airway?
answer_text: 2. Use an adult AMBU bag and a pediatric mask over the laryngectomy stoma to provide ventilation.
course_name: 2021 RESPIRATORY ICU COMPETENCY

question_text:
Laryngectomy patients
What is the appropriate way to ventilate with a bag/mask for a laryngectomy patient without an artificial airway?
answer_text: 3. Intubate through the mouth with an ETT and provide ventilation with the AMBU bag.
course_name: 2021 RESPIRATORY ICU COMPETENCY

question_text:
Laryngectomy patients
What is the appropriate way to ventilate with a bag/mask for a laryngectomy patient without an artificial airway?
answer_text: 4. Do not use an AMBU bag for laryngectomy patients.

question_text: 75 year-old male on Rivaroxaban 15mg daily for atrial fibrillation (CHA2DS2VASc=6) presents to the ED with dizziness, hypotension (BP 80/50), and black tarry stools. Hgb=7, Hct=22.1, plt=193, SCr=2.46 (baseline 1.7). His last dose of Rivaroxaban was 6 hours ago.  The ED provider asks for your recommendation on reversal of Rivaroxaban. Using the NSH reference guide, what will you recommend?
answer_text: a.	Patient is not having a major, life-threatening bleed; Hold Rivaroxaban, provide supportive care and control bleeding site until the drug is out his system.
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY ANTICOAGULATION REVERSAL AND PERIPROCEDURAL MANAGEMENT

question_text: 75 year-old male on Rivaroxaban 15mg daily for atrial fibrillation (CHA2DS2VASc=6) presents to the ED with dizziness, hypotension (BP 80/50), and black tarry stools. Hgb=7, Hct=22.1, plt=193, SCr=2.46 (baseline 1.7). His last dose of Rivaroxaban was 6 hours ago.  The ED provider asks for your recommendation on reversal of Rivaroxaban. Using the NSH reference guide, what will you recommend?
answer_text: b.	Patient is having a major, life-threatening bleed; administer high dose andexanet alfa: 800mg IV bolus followed by continuous infusion of 8mg/min for up to 120 minutes
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY ANTICOAGULATION REVERSAL AND PERIPROCEDURAL MANAGEMENT

question_text: 75 year-old male on Rivaroxaban 15mg daily for atrial fibrillation (CHA2DS2VASc=6) presents to the ED with dizziness, hypotension (BP 80/50), and black tarry stools. Hgb=7, Hct=22.1, plt=193, SCr=2.46 (baseline 1.7). His last dose of Rivaroxaban was 6 hours ago.  The ED provider asks for your recommendation on reversal of Rivaroxaban. Using the NSH reference guide, what will you recommend?
answer_text: c.	Patient is having a major, life-threatening bleed; administer low dose andexanet alfa: 400mg IV bolus followed by continuous infusion of 4mg/min for up to 120 minutes
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY ANTICOAGULATION REVERSAL AND PERIPROCEDURAL MANAGEMENT

question_text: 75 year-old male on Rivaroxaban 15mg daily for atrial fibrillation (CHA2DS2VASc=6) presents to the ED with dizziness, hypotension (BP 80/50), and black tarry stools. Hgb=7, Hct=22.1, plt=193, SCr=2.46 (baseline 1.7). His last dose of Rivaroxaban was 6 hours ago.  The ED provider asks for your recommendation on reversal of Rivaroxaban. Using the NSH reference guide, what will you recommend?
answer_text: d.	Patient is having a major, life-threatening bleed; administer idarucizumab 5g IV as 2 consecutive doses of 2.5mg each
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY ANTICOAGULATION REVERSAL AND PERIPROCEDURAL MANAGEMENT

question_text: Due to their high risk for thrombotic events, anticoagulant reversal agents should only be used to treat major, life-threatening bleeding events. Which of the following are considered a major, life-threatening bleed?
answer_text: a.	Bleeding at a critical site such as intracranial hemorrhage, CNS bleeds (intraocular, spinal), thoracic, intra-abdominal (not including intraluminal GI bleeding)
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY ANTICOAGULATION REVERSAL AND PERIPROCEDURAL MANAGEMENT

question_text: Due to their high risk for thrombotic events, anticoagulant reversal agents should only be used to treat major, life-threatening bleeding events. Which of the following are considered a major, life-threatening bleed?
answer_text: b.	Bleeding that results in hemodynamic instability such as hypotension (SBP <90 mmHg or a drop in SBP >40 mmHg from baseline), tachycardia, or makers of poor organ perfusion (ex. UOP < 0.5mL/kg/hr)
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY ANTICOAGULATION REVERSAL AND PERIPROCEDURAL MANAGEMENT

question_text: Due to their high risk for thrombotic events, anticoagulant reversal agents should only be used to treat major, life-threatening bleeding events. Which of the following are considered a major, life-threatening bleed?
answer_text: c.	Overt bleeding resulting in hemoglobin drop of 2 g/dL or more from baseline
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY ANTICOAGULATION REVERSAL AND PERIPROCEDURAL MANAGEMENT

question_text: Due to their high risk for thrombotic events, anticoagulant reversal agents should only be used to treat major, life-threatening bleeding events. Which of the following are considered a major, life-threatening bleed?
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY ANTICOAGULATION REVERSAL AND PERIPROCEDURAL MANAGEMENT

question_text: 68 year-old male is taking warfarin 5mg daily and aspirin 81mg daily for prophylaxis due to a mechanical mitral valve. The physician asks for your recommendation on how long to hold warfarin and aspirin prior to squamous cell skin cancer excision. Using the NSH reference guide, what will you recommend?
answer_text: a.	This is a low bleed risk procedure; hold warfarin for 5 days or until INR <2 and it is not required to hold aspirin. The patient has a high risk for perioperative VTE, consider prophylactic heparin or enoxaparin while warfarin is being held.
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY ANTICOAGULATION REVERSAL AND PERIPROCEDURAL MANAGEMENT

The physician asks for your recommendation on how long to hold warfarin and aspirin prior to squamous cell skin cancer excision. Using the NSH reference guide, what will you recommend?
answer_text: b.	This is a minimal bleed risk procedure that may not require holding warfarin or aspirin. The patient has a high risk for perioperative VTE, and if the provider does wish to hold anticoagulation, consider prophylactic heparin or enoxaparin while warfarin is being held.
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY ANTICOAGULATION REVERSAL AND PERIPROCEDURAL MANAGEMENT

question_text: A 72 year old male presents to the ED after a fall. The patient is determined to have a severe hip fracture and the ortho surgeon consulted would like to perform emergent hip replacement surgery. The patient is taking Clopidogrel 75mg daily for a history of NSTEMI that occurred 12 months ago. The last dose of clopidogrel was taken 10 hours ago. The surgeon asks how long they should delay surgery to allow for recovery of platelet function. Using the NSH reference guide, what will you recommend?
answer_text: a.	This is a high bleed risk procedure, delay surgery for 5 days from the last dose of clopidogrel to allow for recovery of platelet function.
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY ANTICOAGULATION REVERSAL AND PERIPROCEDURAL MANAGEMENT

question_text: Ms. Jones is a 19 year old G1PO patient that delivered a 36 week baby girl by C section. The patient had a c section related to severe preeclampsia. The patient was on magnesium sulfate for 24 hours after delivery. She is prescribed labetalol 300 mg PO TID. Her blood pressures have ranged 130s-150s/70s-90s since admission.   At 48 hours postpartum, the patient's blood pressure is 176/97.  What is your next nursing action?
course_name: CHANGES TO OB ANTIHYPERTENSIVE MEDICATION ORDERS

answer_text: Wait 30 minutes and recheck the blood pressure again to make sure it was a valid blood pressure reading

question_text: The patient's blood pressure 15 minutes later is 159/110 and she is now complaining of a headache.  What is your next nursing action?
answer_text: Call the provider to determine what regimen to initiate

question_text: The patient's blood pressure 15 minutes later is 159/110 and she is now complaining of a headache.  What is your next nursing action?
answer_text: Review the admission orders to determine which regimen was selected in the communication order
course_name: CHANGES TO OB ANTIHYPERTENSIVE MEDICATION ORDERS

question_text: The patient has a communication order to initiate the IV hydralazine regimen for severe, sustained hypertension.  What is your next nursing action?
answer_text: Place an order for the hydralazine regimen via the OB Hypertension Acute NSH orders as a standing order
course_name: CHANGES TO OB ANTIHYPERTENSIVE MEDICATION ORDERS

question_text:
CASE STUDY
Mr. Jones is a 68 year-old male admitted for a left total hip replacement. He has a history of Type 2 Diabetes, Hypertension and Gout. The discharge plan is to go home with his care partner. The patient has just returned from the PACU and is experiencing mild pain and some nausea but vital signs are stable.

Using C.H.A.D.S., you have addressed the following areas of the POC. What would be an appropriate plan(s) for Change in condition?

Change in Condition - ________________________
High-Risk Comorbidities - Therapeutic Regimen Management (r/t DM and HTN)
Admission Diagnosis - Knowledge Deficit
Discharge Planning - Knowledge Deficit
Safety - At Risk to Fall
course_name: FY2021 INTERDISCIPLINARY PLAN OF CARE: NURSING

question_text: 10.	During a code pink, stop any visitor or employee that passes through with any item large enough to fit an infant in. Say "we have an infant alert and I notice you have an object that could conceal an infant, I apologize for the delay but would you mind opening the (item) so that we can clear you to leave the hospital?" If no infant seen thank them, apologize for any delay and ask them to wait for security to avoid being stopped again. If they refuse to let you look in object notify security immediately. Alert other employees to help you. A staff member may follow them at a safe distance. Do not attempt to detain them
course_name: WSU EMERGENCY CODES _UCS

question_text: Venovenous (VV) ECMO only supports the heart.

question_text: There are many different indications for ECMO, including but not limited to: Flu, Covid-19, Asthma, Heart Attack, Cardiogenic Shock, and Septic Shock
course_name: FY2021 ICU ECMO: EXTRACORPOREAL MEMBRANE OXYGENATION

question_text: There are many different indications for ECMO, including but not limited to: Flu, Covid-19, Asthma, Heart Attack, Cardiogenic Shock, and Septic Shock
course_name: FY2021 ICU ECMO: EXTRACORPOREAL MEMBRANE OXYGENATION

question_text: The ICU nurse will be responsible for documenting the head to toe assessment as well as documenting on the ECMO flowsheet.
course_name: FY2021 ICU ECMO: EXTRACORPOREAL MEMBRANE OXYGENATION

question_text: There will always be an ECMO designee at the bedside and an ECMO physician in close proximity to the patient.

answer_text: a.	Use the PALS dosing sheet in the pediatric medication tray of the Broselow Code Cart to verify the correct exact dose in mg and mL based on the patient's weight
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY NEONATAL INFANT PEDIATRIC RESUSCITATION COMPETENCY

question_text: Which of the below is INCORRECT regarding the preferred way to administer 0.01mg/ kg epinephrine dose for PEA to a 9 kg infant in the ED:
answer_text: b.	Using the 1mg/ 10mL epinephrine Abboject in the pediatric medication drawer, withdraw 0.9ml (0.09mg) epinephrine into a syringe with appropriate markings of measurement using a transfer device (Rapidfill connector or stopcock)
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY NEONATAL INFANT PEDIATRIC RESUSCITATION COMPETENCY

question_text: Which of the below is INCORRECT regarding the preferred way to administer 0.01mg/ kg epinephrine dose for PEA to a 9 kg infant in the ED:
answer_text: c.	Using the 1mg/ 10mL epinephrine Abboject in the pediatric medication drawer, inject  0.9ml (0.09mg) epinephrine dose into the infant's IV or IO access directly from the 1mg/ 10ml epinephrine Abboject syringe.
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY NEONATAL INFANT PEDIATRIC RESUSCITATION COMPETENCY

question_text: Which of the following is CORRECT regarding Neonatal Resuscitation?

course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY NEONATAL INFANT PEDIATRIC RESUSCITATION COMPETENCY

question_text: Which of the following is CORRECT regarding Neonatal Resuscitation?
answer_text: b.	Lidocaine and amiodarone are the primary treatment options for pulseless ventricular fibrillation and ventricular tachycardia in NRP the algorithm.
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY NEONATAL INFANT PEDIATRIC RESUSCITATION COMPETENCY

question_text: Which of the following is CORRECT regarding Neonatal Resuscitation?

course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY NEONATAL INFANT PEDIATRIC RESUSCITATION COMPETENCY

question_text: Which of the following is INCORRECT regarding Infant and Pediatric Resuscitation using PALS?

question_text: Which of the following is INCORRECT regarding Infant and Pediatric Resuscitation using PALS?

question_text: Which of the following is INCORRECT regarding Infant and Pediatric Resuscitation using PALS?

question_text: Why is the Distress Screening completed?
answer_text: a)	We are told to do it
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: Why is the Distress Screening completed?
answer_text: b)	To remain accredited with COC, providing a high standard of care
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: Why is the Distress Screening completed?
answer_text: c)	To assess level of distress of patients, identify their needs and establish quality care and assistance
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: Why is the Distress Screening completed?
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: When would it be more appropriate to use a 2013 versus 1013?
answer_text: a)	The patient is incapacitated by alcohol, drugs or other substance on a re-occurring basis and present as a substantial risk of imminent harm to self and/or others if left untreated
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: When would it be more appropriate to use a 2013 versus 1013?
answer_text: b)	The patient has mental illness and presents as a substantial risk of harm to self or others
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: When would it be more appropriate to use a 2013 versus 1013?
answer_text: c)	The patient has only mental illness and presents substantial risk of imminent harm to self or others with no primary diagnosis of alcoholism or other substance abuse nor dependency, he/she presents as a substantial risk of imminent harm to self or others.
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: When would it be more appropriate to use a 2013 versus 1013?
answer_text: d)	Patient is unable to care for his/her own physical health or safety as to create an imminently life-threatening crisis
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: If a patient score 4-7
answer_text: a)	Review and sign form, assess patient for any immediate needs/concerns

answer_text: b)	RN signs form, which is scanned into EMR

question_text: In handling a patient, who is expressing suicidal /homicidal ideation, but is on the phone, which of the following is not part of the protocol?
answer_text: a)	Keep the patient on the phone
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: In handling a patient, who is expressing suicidal /homicidal ideation, but is on the phone, which of the following is not part of the protocol?
answer_text: b)	Notify the supervisor or another staff member to locate the patient's address
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: In handling a patient, who is expressing suicidal /homicidal ideation, but is on the phone, which of the following is not part of the protocol?
answer_text: c)	Call 911 to go to the patient's location
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: In handling a patient, who is expressing suicidal /homicidal ideation, but is on the phone, which of the following is not part of the protocol?
answer_text: d)	Do not document in patient's medical chart since the patient is not in the office.
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: Which of the following processes would be different in handling a  type 2 patients  versus  handling type  1 patients?
answer_text: a)	Follow the Chain of Command Communication for your area and notify OSW/Behavioral Health Services, notify MD if available
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: Which of the following processes would be different in handling a  type 2 patients  versus  handling type  1 patients?
answer_text: b)	Do not leave patient alone
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: Which of the following processes would be different in handling a  type 2 patients  versus  handling type  1 patients?
answer_text: c)	Call 911 first, then call security, if available, to make aware of the situation.
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: Which of the following processes would be different in handling a  type 2 patients  versus  handling type  1 patients?
answer_text: d)	Document facts of the event in the patient ΓÇÿs medical chart and complete an incident report
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: In handling type 1 patients, which of the following processes should be utilized?
answer_text: a)	Follow the chain of command for your area and notify the OSW/Behavioral Health Services
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: In handling type 1 patients, which of the following processes should be utilized?
answer_text: b)	Call Security for your respective location; patient should not be left alone
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: In handling type 1 patients, which of the following processes should be utilized?
answer_text: c)	If OSW does not respond within a reasonable timeframe, call the Psych-Oncology Coordinator, respective Supervisor/ Lead OSW, or BHS, notify MD, if available.
course_name: FY2021 DISTRESS SCREENING AND MANAGEMENT OF THE PATIENT NEEDING A 1013 ORDER

question_text: In handling type 1 patients, which of the following processes should be utilized?
answer_text: d)	Initiate a 1013 and transfer process with appropriate documentation

question_text: A patient on the cardiac unit with episodes of non sustained ventricular tachycardia loses pulse and a code blue event is called on the unit. The patient's rhythm is quickly identified as ventricular tachycardia and the patient is successfully defibrillated, returning to NSR with a pulse. The physician requests an amiodarone bolus be given stat and a drip initiated. Which of the following is true?
answer_text: a.	The pharmacist should remove the amiodarone bolus bag 1 from tray 1 of the adult code cart and prepare a 300mg bolus syringe for IV push.
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY CODE BLUE AND EMERGENCY CART COMPETENCY

question_text: A patient on the cardiac unit with episodes of non sustained ventricular tachycardia loses pulse and a code blue event is called on the unit. The patient's rhythm is quickly identified as ventricular tachycardia and the patient is successfully defibrillated, returning to NSR with a pulse. The physician requests an amiodarone bolus be given stat and a drip initiated. Which of the following is true?
answer_text: b.	The pharmacist should remove the amiodarone bolus bag 2 from tray 1 of the adult code cart and prepare a 150mg bolus syringe for IV push.
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY CODE BLUE AND EMERGENCY CART COMPETENCY

question_text: A patient on the cardiac unit with episodes of non sustained ventricular tachycardia loses pulse and a code blue event is called on the unit. The patient's rhythm is quickly identified as ventricular tachycardia and the patient is successfully defibrillated, returning to NSR with a pulse. The physician requests an amiodarone bolus be given stat and a drip initiated. Which of the following is true?
answer_text: c.	The pharmacist should disregard the bolus order and hand the nurse the premixed drip from drawer 1 of the code cart, instructing the RN to bolus from the bag.
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY CODE BLUE AND EMERGENCY CART COMPETENCY

question_text: A patient on the cardiac unit with episodes of non sustained ventricular tachycardia loses pulse and a code blue event is called on the unit. The patient's rhythm is quickly identified as ventricular tachycardia and the patient is successfully defibrillated, returning to NSR with a pulse. The physician requests an amiodarone bolus be given stat and a drip initiated. Which of the following is true?
answer_text: d.	The pharmacist should obtain a stat amiodarone 150mg/ 100ml IVPB which is not in the adult code cart to infuse over 10 minutes, (not IV push, as the patient now has a pulse), then proceed with the premixed drip at 1mg/ minute.
course_name: FY2021 PHARMACY CODE BLUE AND EMERGENCY CART COMPETENCY

question_text: A patient with advanced renal cell carcinoma presents to your clinic for treatment today. The patient has been receiving nivolumab 240mg IV q 2 weeks for the past 20 weeks. You observe that the patient's AST/ALT have risen by more than 5 x ULN and you inform the provider. Which of the following are all appropriate for management of this potential immune-mediated adverse reaction to nivolumab?
answer_text: a.	Discontinue nivolumab and consult Gastroenterology
course_name: 2021 MANAGEMENT OF IMMUNOTHERAPY RELATED TOXICITIES

question_text: A patient with advanced renal cell carcinoma presents to your clinic for treatment today. The patient has been receiving nivolumab 240mg IV q 2 weeks for the past 20 weeks. You observe that the patient's AST/ALT have risen by more than 5 x ULN and you inform the provider. Which of the following are all appropriate for management of this potential immune-mediated adverse reaction to nivolumab?
answer_text: b.	Initiate high dose steroids followed by infliximab
course_name: 2021 MANAGEMENT OF IMMUNOTHERAPY RELATED TOXICITIES

question_text: A patient with advanced renal cell carcinoma presents to your clinic for treatment today. The patient has been receiving nivolumab 240mg IV q 2 weeks for the past 20 weeks. You observe that the patient's AST/ALT have risen by more than 5 x ULN and you inform the provider. Which of the following are all appropriate for management of this potential immune-mediated adverse reaction to nivolumab?
answer_text: c.	Initiate prednisone 1-2mg/kg/day follow by corticosteroid taper and consider mycophenolate for persistent severe hepatitis despite high dose corticosteroids.
course_name: 2021 MANAGEMENT OF IMMUNOTHERAPY RELATED TOXICITIES

question_text: A 65 year old female patient with metastatic gastric cancer presents to your clinic for evaluation due to complaints of frequent diarrhea. After further questioning, she reports approximately 4 loose stools each day beginning three days ago. She is receiving treatment with pembrolizumab 200mg every 3 weeks with the last treatment date being one week ago. What is the most appropriate management of this Grade 2 irAE?
answer_text: a.	Hold pembrolizumab and initiate IV methylprednisolone 1mg/kg/day
course_name: 2021 MANAGEMENT OF IMMUNOTHERAPY RELATED TOXICITIES

question_text: A 65 year old female patient with metastatic gastric cancer presents to your clinic for evaluation due to complaints of frequent diarrhea. After further questioning, she reports approximately 4 loose stools each day beginning three days ago. She is receiving treatment with pembrolizumab 200mg every 3 weeks with the last treatment date being one week ago. What is the most appropriate management of this Grade 2 irAE?
answer_text: b.	If there is no response after starting IV steroids in 2-3 days, may increase dose to 2mg/kg/day. Change to prednisone when appropriate
course_name: 2021 MANAGEMENT OF IMMUNOTHERAPY RELATED TOXICITIES

question_text: A 65 year old female patient with metastatic gastric cancer presents to your clinic for evaluation due to complaints of frequent diarrhea. After further questioning, she reports approximately 4 loose stools each day beginning three days ago. She is receiving treatment with pembrolizumab 200mg every 3 weeks with the last treatment date being one week ago. What is the most appropriate management of this Grade 2 irAE?
answer_text: c.	Treat with steroids until symptoms improve to Grade 1 or less. Permanently discontinue pembrolizumab.
course_name: 2021 MANAGEMENT OF IMMUNOTHERAPY RELATED TOXICITIES
